Note:
Runtime priority task scheduler — the public strict-priority work dispatcher
for the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. The actual thread mechanism comes
from the completed thread_core primitives (which delegate to the per-platform
OS thread create/join), the mutual exclusion from the runtime mutex object,
and the blocking wait/wake from the runtime condition-variable object. This
module does NOT re-implement threads, locks, or wait queues; it composes them
into a fixed-worker, strict-priority scheduler that always runs the
highest-priority ready task before any lower-priority one.

Distinction from thread_pool: a thread pool runs tasks in submission order
(FIFO) across its workers. This scheduler maintains one FIFO ready-queue PER
priority level and a worker always pops from the highest-priority non-empty
level first. Within a single level the order is FIFO; across levels it is
strict priority. The two modules are intentionally separate dispatch
disciplines and neither duplicates the other.

A task is a (function-pointer, argument) pair. A worker invokes it through
the assembly indirect-call primitive call_indirect_1, so any module-level
Process whose address is taken with the $name operator and that takes a
single Integer argument can be scheduled.

Scheduler object layout (64 bytes):
    offset 0:  mutex        — RuntimeMutex guarding all scheduler state
    offset 8:  cv_work      — RuntimeCondVar signalled when a task is enqueued
    offset 16: cv_drained   — RuntimeCondVar broadcast when pending reaches 0
    offset 24: pending      — count of submitted-but-not-yet-completed tasks
    offset 32: shutdown     — 0 running, 1 shutting down (workers must drain+exit)
    offset 40: worker_count — number of worker threads
    offset 48: worker_tids  — pointer to an array of worker_count thread ids
    offset 56: levels       — pointer to an array of SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS ring pointers

Per-level ready queue (a growable FIFO ring, 32 bytes):
    offset 0:  buffer   — pointer to capacity * 16 bytes of (fn,arg) slots
    offset 8:  capacity — number of slots the buffer can hold
    offset 16: count    — number of tasks currently queued
    offset 24: head     — index of the front (oldest) task

Each ring slot is 16 bytes: the function pointer at +0, the argument at +8.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/thread_core.runa" as Thread
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/mutex.runa" as Mutex
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/condition_variable.runa" as CondVar
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: Number of strict-priority levels: 0 is highest, SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS-1 lowest
Constant SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS as Integer is 4

Note: Initial slot capacity of each per-level ready ring before its first grow
Constant SCHED_RING_INIT_CAPACITY as Integer is 8

Note: Scheduler object layout
Constant SCHED_SIZE as Integer is 64
Constant SCHED_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK as Integer is 8
Constant SCHED_OFF_CV_DRAINED as Integer is 16
Constant SCHED_OFF_PENDING as Integer is 24
Constant SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN as Integer is 32
Constant SCHED_OFF_WORKER_COUNT as Integer is 40
Constant SCHED_OFF_WORKER_TIDS as Integer is 48
Constant SCHED_OFF_LEVELS as Integer is 56

Note: Per-level ring layout
Constant RING_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant RING_OFF_BUFFER as Integer is 0
Constant RING_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 8
Constant RING_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 16
Constant RING_OFF_HEAD as Integer is 24

Note: Ring slot geometry — a (function-pointer, argument) pair
Constant SCHED_SLOT_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant SCHED_SLOT_OFF_ARG as Integer is 8

Note: Status codes returned by the scheduler API
Constant SCHED_OK as Integer is 0
Constant SCHED_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant SCHED_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 2

Process called "ring_new" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Build one per-level ready ring: a growable circular buffer of (fn,arg)
    slots that preserves FIFO order within its priority level.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 32-byte ring header and a slot buffer of capacity * 16 bytes.
    A non-positive requested capacity is clamped to 1 so the ring is always
    valid and the doubling grow always makes forward progress. On buffer
    allocation failure the header is released and 0 is returned.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two allocations, done once per level at scheduler construction. The buffer
    grows by doubling thereafter, giving amortized O(1) enqueue.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cap be capacity
    If cap is less than 1:
        Set cap to 1
    End If

    Let ring be proc allocate from Memory with RING_SIZE
    If ring is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let buffer_bytes be cap multiplied by SCHED_SLOT_SIZE
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Memory with buffer_bytes
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with ring
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_BUFFER, buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_CAPACITY, cap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_HEAD, 0
    Return ring
End Process

Process called "ring_push" takes ring as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Append a task to the tail of one level's ready ring, preserving FIFO order
    among tasks of equal priority. When the ring is full it is grown so no
    submission is ever dropped.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    When count equals capacity, double the capacity, allocate a new buffer, and
    copy the existing tasks into it in FIFO order (walking from head forward,
    wrapping once), then free the old buffer and reset head to 0. After any
    needed grow, the new task is written at the tail slot
    ((head + count) wrapped into capacity) and count is incremented. A failed
    grow allocation returns SCHED_ERR_ALLOC and leaves the ring unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Amortized O(1): most pushes write a single slot; a grow copies count slots
    but doubling makes the copy cost amortize to a constant per task.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Called while the scheduler mutex is held, so the ring fields are observed
    and mutated under mutual exclusion.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_CAPACITY
    Let cnt be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_COUNT
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_HEAD
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_BUFFER

    If cnt is equal to cap:
        Let new_cap be cap multiplied by 2
        Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by SCHED_SLOT_SIZE
        Let new_buffer be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
        If new_buffer is equal to 0:
            Return SCHED_ERR_ALLOC
        End If

        Let k be 0
        While k is less than cnt:
            Let src_idx be head plus k
            If src_idx is greater than or equal to cap:
                Set src_idx to src_idx minus cap
            End If
            Let src_off be src_idx multiplied by SCHED_SLOT_SIZE
            Let dst_off be k multiplied by SCHED_SLOT_SIZE
            Let slot_fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with buffer, src_off
            Let slot_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with buffer, src_off plus SCHED_SLOT_OFF_ARG
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_buffer, dst_off, slot_fn
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_buffer, dst_off plus SCHED_SLOT_OFF_ARG, slot_arg
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Memory with buffer
        Set buffer to new_buffer
        Set cap to new_cap
        Set head to 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_BUFFER, new_buffer
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_CAPACITY, new_cap
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_HEAD, 0
    End If

    Let tail be head plus cnt
    If tail is greater than or equal to cap:
        Set tail to tail minus cap
    End If
    Let tail_off be tail multiplied by SCHED_SLOT_SIZE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer, tail_off, fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer, tail_off plus SCHED_SLOT_OFF_ARG, arg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_COUNT, cnt plus 1
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "ring_destroy" takes ring as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release a per-level ring and its slot buffer at scheduler teardown.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Free the slot buffer (if present) then the ring header. A null ring is a
    no-op so teardown of a partially constructed scheduler is safe.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two deallocations. Cold path: once per level at shutdown.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Must be called only when no worker can still reference the ring (after
    shutdown has joined all workers).
    @End Security_Scope

    If ring is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_OK
    End If
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_BUFFER
    If buffer is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with buffer
    End If
    proc deallocate from Memory with ring
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_total_ready" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many tasks are ready across every priority level. Workers use
    this as the wait predicate (no work means park) and as the drain test.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Sum the count field of each per-level ring. A null ring slot contributes
    nothing, which keeps the scan safe during partial construction.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    A bounded scan over SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS rings (a constant), each one
    field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Called while the scheduler mutex is held so the per-level counts are read
    under mutual exclusion.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let levels be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_LEVELS
    If levels is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let total be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS:
        Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with levels, i multiplied by 8
        If ring is not equal to 0:
            Let cnt be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_COUNT
            Set total to total plus cnt
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return total
End Process

Process called "scheduler_free_resources" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release every resource a scheduler owns. Shared by the normal shutdown path
    (after workers are joined) and by every partial-failure path in
    scheduler_new, so cleanup logic lives in exactly one place.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Each field is read and freed only when non-zero, because scheduler_new zero
    initializes all fields up front and fills them in stages. Destroy the per
    level rings and their array, the worker-tid array, both condition variables,
    and the mutex, then free the scheduler object itself.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    A bounded number of deallocations plus the sync-object destroys. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Must not be called while any worker thread can still touch the scheduler;
    the shutdown path joins all workers first.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let levels be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_LEVELS
    If levels is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS:
            Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with levels, i multiplied by 8
            If ring is not equal to 0:
                proc ring_destroy with ring
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc deallocate from Memory with levels
    End If

    Let tids be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_TIDS
    If tids is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
    End If

    Let cv_work be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK
    If cv_work is not equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv_work
    End If

    Let cv_drained be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_DRAINED
    If cv_drained is not equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv_drained
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    If mtx is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
    End If

    proc deallocate from Memory with sched
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_worker_main" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The body of every worker thread. A worker always executes the
    highest-priority ready task before any lower-priority one, parking on the
    work condition variable when nothing is ready, and exiting only once
    shutdown has been requested AND every level is drained.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Loop: acquire the mutex; while there is no ready work and shutdown is not
    set, wait on cv_work (the wait re-checks the predicate on every wake, so
    spurious wakes and broadcast storms are handled correctly). If shutdown is
    set and nothing is ready, release and return. Otherwise scan the levels
    from highest priority (0) upward and pop the front task of the first
    non-empty level by reading its head slot and advancing head with wraparound.
    Release the mutex, run the task through call_indirect_1, then re-acquire,
    decrement pending, and broadcast cv_drained when pending hits 0 so
    scheduler_wait_idle can return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    No busy-waiting: idle workers sleep in the OS until a submit signals them.
    Task selection is a bounded scan over SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS levels. The
    task runs with the mutex released so workers execute in parallel.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Entered only via thread_create from scheduler_new with a valid scheduler.
    The task function pointer was validated by the submitter; an indirect call
    to a corrupt pointer is the caller's responsibility, as documented on
    scheduler_submit.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv_work be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK
    Let cv_drained be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_DRAINED
    Let levels be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_LEVELS

    Loop forever:
        proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

        Note: Park while nothing is ready and we are not shutting down. The
        Note: predicate is re-evaluated on every iteration so each wake (real
        Note: or spurious) rechecks before proceeding.
        Let waiting be 1
        While waiting is equal to 1:
            Let ready be proc scheduler_total_ready with sched
            Let shutdown_flag be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN
            If ready is equal to 0:
                If shutdown_flag is equal to 0:
                    proc condvar_wait from CondVar with cv_work, mtx
                Otherwise:
                    Set waiting to 0
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set waiting to 0
            End If
        End While

        Note: Exit only when shutting down AND fully drained.
        Let shutdown_now be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN
        Let ready_now be proc scheduler_total_ready with sched
        If shutdown_now is not equal to 0:
            If ready_now is equal to 0:
                proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: Select the highest-priority non-empty level (0 is highest).
        Let found be 0 minus 1
        Let lvl be 0
        While lvl is less than SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS:
            Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with levels, lvl multiplied by 8
            Let ring_count be 0
            If ring is not equal to 0:
                Set ring_count to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, RING_OFF_COUNT
            End If
            If ring_count is greater than 0:
                Set found to lvl
                Set lvl to SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS
            Otherwise:
                Set lvl to lvl plus 1
            End If
        End While

        Note: found is always >= 0 here because ready_now was greater than 0.
        Let sel_ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with levels, found multiplied by 8
        Let sel_buffer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sel_ring, RING_OFF_BUFFER
        Let sel_cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sel_ring, RING_OFF_CAPACITY
        Let sel_head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sel_ring, RING_OFF_HEAD
        Let sel_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sel_ring, RING_OFF_COUNT
        Let head_off be sel_head multiplied by SCHED_SLOT_SIZE
        Let task_fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sel_buffer, head_off
        Let task_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sel_buffer, head_off plus SCHED_SLOT_OFF_ARG
        Let new_head be sel_head plus 1
        If new_head is greater than or equal to sel_cap:
            Set new_head to 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sel_ring, RING_OFF_HEAD, new_head
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sel_ring, RING_OFF_COUNT, sel_count minus 1

        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx

        Note: Run the task with the lock released so workers run in parallel.
        proc call_indirect_1 from Call with task_fn, task_arg

        proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
        Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING
        Set pending to pending minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING, pending
        If pending is equal to 0:
            proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv_drained
        End If
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    End Loop

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "scheduler_new" takes worker_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a running priority scheduler: its synchronization objects, one
    ready ring per priority level, the worker-tid array, and the worker threads
    themselves. After this returns non-zero the scheduler is live and accepts
    submissions.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    A non-positive worker_count is resolved to the hardware concurrency (and
    floored at 1). All scheduler fields are zero-initialized first so the shared
    scheduler_free_resources can clean up from any failure point. The mutex,
    both condition variables, the levels array, each per-level ring, and the
    tid array are created in turn; any allocation failure unwinds through
    scheduler_free_resources and returns 0. Workers are spawned last via
    thread_create with the $name address of scheduler_worker_main and the
    scheduler pointer as the argument; if a spawn fails mid-way, shutdown is
    requested, the already-spawned workers are joined, resources are freed, and
    0 is returned.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path. Cost is dominated by the worker_count thread creations (each a
    kernel operation). Per-level rings start small and grow on demand.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use. No partially
    constructed scheduler and no leaked threads or memory escape this call.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let workers be worker_count
    If workers is less than 1:
        Set workers to proc thread_hardware_concurrency from Thread
    End If
    If workers is less than 1:
        Set workers to 1
    End If

    Let sched be proc allocate from Memory with SCHED_SIZE
    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Zero-initialize all fields so scheduler_free_resources is null-safe
    Note: at every failure point below.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_DRAINED, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_TIDS, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_LEVELS, 0

    Let mtx be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX, mtx

    Let cv_work be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If cv_work is equal to 0:
        proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK, cv_work

    Let cv_drained be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If cv_drained is equal to 0:
        proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_DRAINED, cv_drained

    Let levels_bytes be SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS multiplied by 8
    Let levels be proc allocate from Memory with levels_bytes
    If levels is equal to 0:
        proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
        Return 0
    End If
    Let z be 0
    While z is less than SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with levels, z multiplied by 8, 0
        Set z to z plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_LEVELS, levels

    Let li be 0
    While li is less than SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS:
        Let ring be proc ring_new with SCHED_RING_INIT_CAPACITY
        If ring is equal to 0:
            proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with levels, li multiplied by 8, ring
        Set li to li plus 1
    End While

    Let tids_bytes be workers multiplied by 8
    Let tids be proc allocate from Memory with tids_bytes
    If tids is equal to 0:
        proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tz be 0
    While tz is less than workers:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, tz multiplied by 8, 0
        Set tz to tz plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_TIDS, tids
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_COUNT, workers

    Note: Spawn the workers. Their entry is the real code address of
    Note: scheduler_worker_main taken via the $name function-pointer operator.
    Let entry_fn be $scheduler_worker_main
    Let wi be 0
    While wi is less than workers:
        Let tid be proc thread_create from Thread with entry_fn, sched
        If tid is equal to 0:
            Note: A spawn failed. Request shutdown, wake any started workers,
            Note: join them, free everything, and report failure.
            proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1
            proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv_work
            proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx

            Let ji be 0
            While ji is less than wi:
                Let started_tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tids, ji multiplied by 8
                If started_tid is not equal to 0:
                    proc thread_join from Thread with started_tid
                End If
                Set ji to ji plus 1
            End While

            proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, wi multiplied by 8, tid
        Set wi to wi plus 1
    End While

    Return sched
End Process

Process called "scheduler_submit" takes sched as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer, priority as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Enqueue a task at a given priority. The task becomes immediately eligible
    and is guaranteed to run before any task of strictly lower priority that is
    submitted at or after this point.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Clamp the priority into [0, SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS-1] so out-of-range values
    are dispatched at the nearest valid level. Under the mutex, push the
    (fn,arg) pair onto that level's ring (growing it if full), increment
    pending, and signal cv_work to wake one parked worker. A failed ring grow
    surfaces SCHED_ERR_ALLOC and does not change pending.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex round-trip, an amortized O(1) ring push, and one condvar signal
    (a single futex wake). Hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. The function pointer must reference a
    live module-level Process taking one Integer; the worker calls it through
    call_indirect_1.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let level be priority
    If level is less than 0:
        Set level to 0
    End If
    If level is greater than or equal to SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS:
        Set level to SCHED_PRIORITY_LEVELS minus 1
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv_work be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK
    Let levels be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_LEVELS

    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with levels, level multiplied by 8
    Let push_rc be proc ring_push with ring, fn, arg
    If push_rc is not equal to SCHED_OK:
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
        Return push_rc
    End If
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING, pending plus 1
    proc condvar_signal from CondVar with cv_work
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_pending" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many submitted tasks have not yet completed (queued plus
    currently executing). Used by callers polling for progress.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the pending counter under the mutex so the value is a consistent
    snapshot rather than a torn read against a concurrent worker decrement.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex round-trip and a single field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null scheduler returns 0. The value is advisory and may change immediately
    after the call returns.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return pending
End Process

Process called "scheduler_wait_idle" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until every submitted task has completed. Used to
    join a batch of work without polling.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the mutex, wait on cv_drained while pending is greater than 0. The
    wait re-checks pending on every wake, so it returns exactly when the last
    task's completion drives pending to 0 and broadcasts cv_drained. If nothing
    is pending on entry it returns immediately.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    No busy-waiting: the caller sleeps in the OS until the drain broadcast.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. On return the mutex is released and
    no obligation is left to the caller.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv_drained be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_DRAINED
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING
    While pending is greater than 0:
        proc condvar_wait from CondVar with cv_drained, mtx
        Set pending to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_PENDING
    End While
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_yield" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Cooperative hint that the calling thread is willing to relinquish the CPU so
    other ready threads — including scheduler workers — can run.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to thread_yield, the platform-routed scheduler yield primitive.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One yield syscall; no allocation or locking.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Advisory hint only; never blocks indefinitely.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc thread_yield from Thread
End Process

Process called "scheduler_worker_count" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report the number of worker threads servicing this scheduler.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the worker_count field. The value is fixed for the scheduler's
    lifetime, so no lock is required.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null scheduler returns 0.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_COUNT
End Process

Process called "scheduler_shutdown" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stop the scheduler cleanly: let workers finish every already-queued task,
    then exit and join them, then release all resources. After this returns the
    scheduler pointer is invalid.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the mutex, set the shutdown flag and broadcast cv_work so every parked
    worker wakes; workers then drain all levels before returning (see
    scheduler_worker_main). Join each worker thread, then free every resource
    through scheduler_free_resources.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path. Blocks until all queued tasks finish and all workers join.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. Must not be called concurrently with
    itself; one shutdown owns the teardown.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv_work be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CV_WORK

    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1
    proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv_work
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx

    Let worker_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_COUNT
    Let tids be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_WORKER_TIDS
    If tids is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than worker_count:
            Let tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tids, i multiplied by 8
            If tid is not equal to 0:
                proc thread_join from Thread with tid
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc scheduler_free_resources with sched
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process
